<div id="review_109155961" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/109155961" />
    <a title="Sara" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/304359-sara"><img alt="Sara" src="https://s.gr-assets.com/assets/nophoto/user/f_50x66-6a03a5c12233c941481992b82eea8d23.png" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/109155961?book_show_action=true">Jun 28, 2010</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Sara" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Sara" href="/user/show/304359-sara">Sara</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was ok"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was ok</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9780385423359" href="/book/show/5502.The_Harafish">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/304359-sara?shelf=100-novels">100-novels</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer109155961" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer595366671894347497">This isn&apos;t actually one story, but rather a collection of 10 tales. I didn&apos;t like it because it was almost all exposition, description and getting from A to B. As soon as I was interested in a character and his or her story, it was quickly wrapped up to make way for the next tale, usually about the previous tale&apos;s character&apos;s child. It felt a lot like the book of Genesis: &quot;A begat B, who married C and D and begat E, F and G...&quot; I also didn&apos;t like that there was no sense of the passage of time or</span>
  <span id="freeText595366671894347497" style="display:none">This isn't actually one story, but rather a collection of 10 tales. I didn't like it because it was almost all exposition, description and getting from A to B. As soon as I was interested in a character and his or her story, it was quickly wrapped up to make way for the next tale, usually about the previous tale's character's child. It felt a lot like the book of Genesis: "A begat B, who married C and D and begat E, F and G..." I also didn't like that there was no sense of the passage of time or of the outside world. I thought the first tale could have taken place in the early 1900s, but then there were at least several hundred more years worth of tales and nothing changed. A novel can be private, but this felt like it completely denied the effect that the world can have on a character - the tales were solely about the characters' births, deaths, marriages, children and quests for glory (which are limited to the alley that they all live in). I probably could have given it one star, but he does have a touch of poetry at times, and occasionally an interesting insight into humanity.</span>
  <a data-text-id="595366671894347497" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

