    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_198092414" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/198092414" />
    <a title="Tyler " class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/1096417-tyler"><img alt="Tyler " src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1377822301p2/1096417.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/198092414?book_show_action=true">Aug 13, 2011</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Tyler " class="user" itemprop="url" name="Tyler " href="/user/show/1096417-tyler">Tyler </a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9780385423359" href="/book/show/5502.The_Harafish">review of another edition</a>

          <div><span class="uitext greyText">Recommends it for: </span>
           <span class="uitext reviewText">Fans of Mahfouz; Fans of 20th Century Lit</span></div>

        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/1096417-tyler?shelf=literature">literature</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer198092414" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer4532897996278144428">The Harafish, which translates as “the common people,” traces an Egyptian family’s progress over ten generations in ten chapters. The point is to find out whether good character traits in a family can be handed down, or if they can even recur to the same effect, in later generations. This is a good idea for a book.<br/><br/>The number of characters in this epic means that readers gain in-depth knowledge of only a few. This is not a novel for people looking for character development. The plot has no time, </span>
  <span id="freeText4532897996278144428" style="display:none">The Harafish, which translates as “the common people,” traces an Egyptian family’s progress over ten generations in ten chapters. The point is to find out whether good character traits in a family can be handed down, or if they can even recur to the same effect, in later generations. This is a good idea for a book.<br /><br />The number of characters in this epic means that readers gain in-depth knowledge of only a few. This is not a novel for people looking for character development. The plot has no time, either. About two centuries elapse, but the reader cannot place them as particular epochs in actual history. <br /><br />This narrative, then, is very much one of action and dialog, and the effect is to frame almost every relevant personality trait that might crop up in the context of a single family -- some people get rich, others are highly moral, some kill, some rape, at least one commits suicide, and, most important, many family members are conflicted or confused about what it takes to do the right thing. <br /><br />Other reviewers have called this a “lyrical” story, and in a way it is. The author uses repetition effectively, for example. But whatever lyrical quality the Arabic version has is inevitably lost in translation, and most of the the book reads like a straightforward storytelling. The translation is as good as can be expected, so even with the loss of lyricism in the English the book is still noticeably superior to most of what’s written in this language anyway. That’s a comment upon either the superiority of Arabic literature or the inferiority of English literature -- take your pick.<br /><br />For non-Egyptians this book sheds light on Egyptian social values, as do all of Mahfouz’s books. Apropos of current events, thugs are a leitmotif of the book, and in fact the Arab Spring has brought to the world’s attention the role thugs play in political repression. Certain other interesting and disturbing aspects of Egyptian social values also stand out to readers unfamiliar with Egypt.<br /><br />I give the book three stars and a good recommendation. My favorite Mahfouz novels are the ones written in the 1940’s, and this book comes from a later period in which the author experiments with structural elements of the novel. I breezed through it, but it didn’t grab me the way <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/5499.Midaq_Alley" title="Midaq Alley by Naguib Mahfouz" rel="nofollow noopener">Midaq Alley</a> and <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/7160.The_Beginning_and_the_End" title="The Beginning and the End by Naguib Mahfouz" rel="nofollow noopener">The Beginning and the End</a> did. Nevertheless, it is a Mahfouz, a thoughtful novel that entertains provocative ideas and leads to a quite surprising conclusion. People who have never read this author would enjoy the book, but it is better appreciated by people who have already read his earlier works.</span>
  <a data-text-id="4532897996278144428" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

