<div id="review_2829752652" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2829752652" />
    <a title="Maggie Ayau" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/32279091-maggie-ayau"><img alt="Maggie Ayau" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1547930560p2/32279091.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2829752652?book_show_action=true">Jun 04, 2019</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Maggie Ayau" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Maggie Ayau" href="/user/show/32279091-maggie-ayau">Maggie Ayau</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9780385423359" href="/book/show/5502.The_Harafish">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/32279091-maggie-ayau?shelf=2019-reading-challenge">2019-reading-challenge</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2829752652" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer5191491101570989952">I needed to read this quickly because I recently remembered that I’ve been borrowing it from a friend for over two years now. (Sorry Kyler.) <br/><br/>Another mark in my interest in reading storylines that diverge from a typical arc. This one is more like an actual line. The epic starts at the specific point of discovery of the newborn Ashur al-Nagi outside of a Cairo monestery. Ashur grows up to be a noble and just leader of the clan that rules the alley, respected by the harafish, or the working and low</span>
  <span id="freeText5191491101570989952" style="display:none">I needed to read this quickly because I recently remembered that I’ve been borrowing it from a friend for over two years now. (Sorry Kyler.) <br /><br />Another mark in my interest in reading storylines that diverge from a typical arc. This one is more like an actual line. The epic starts at the specific point of discovery of the newborn Ashur al-Nagi outside of a Cairo monestery. Ashur grows up to be a noble and just leader of the clan that rules the alley, respected by the harafish, or the working and lower classes (translated as “rabble” or “riffraff”, e.g. commoners, from the original Egyptian Arabic). We see the Nagi line unfold over hundreds of years, with each new generation struggling with power, morality, and familial duty. As time stretches on, the fabled Ashur and other early patriarchs (Shams al-Din, Sulayman) evolve more and more into figures of legend, with Ashur eventually becoming the venerated prophet-hero of the Nagi dynasty. Kind of like King Arthur, Aeneas, Abraham, Godric Gryffindor, or Isildur, High King of Gondor.<br /><br />There are some LOVELY, TRULY LOVELY poetic moments and phrases here.<br /><br />Enjoyed the structure. The epic is split into ten tales, which each tale focusing on a different set of descendents and consisting of 50-70 vignettes or sagas. <br /><br />Lots of turnover character-wise. New passion project is making a family tree of the Nagi line. Sometimes I rushed through stories but they really demand to be read slowly and carefully.<br /><br />Besides the sense of clutter around the characters adds to the motion of the epic. The farther out from Ashur we travel with his descendents, the more their names and stories accumulate and jumble. We start to look for patterns to help us maintain the thread between them. Do certain traits get passed down from person to person? Is it the power itself a source of corruption, or is it only corruptible people who are drawn to power?<br /><br />Why did I picture JEFF GOLDBLUM AS AZIZ</span>
  <a data-text-id="5191491101570989952" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


