<div id="review_176148807" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/176148807" />
    <a title="Laura" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/82840-laura"><img alt="Laura" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1465057364p2/82840.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/176148807?book_show_action=true">Jun 12, 2011</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Laura" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Laura" href="/user/show/82840-laura">Laura</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9780385423359" href="/book/show/5502.The_Harafish">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer176148807" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer2237889800089347189">I tried to read this years ago and couldn&apos;t get into it, but when I read it again now, I was hooked. The story moves fast, as in decades fly by with one sentence. It is the epic story of a family descended from a hero, Ashur, who stars in the first story. The subsequent nine stories detail the various downfalls and wild tales of the nine or so (I lost count) generations after him. Like Garcia Marquez&apos;s &quot;One Hundred Years of Solitude,&quot; this story has a mythic and surreal feel to it. Unlike Garcia</span>
  <span id="freeText2237889800089347189" style="display:none">I tried to read this years ago and couldn't get into it, but when I read it again now, I was hooked. The story moves fast, as in decades fly by with one sentence. It is the epic story of a family descended from a hero, Ashur, who stars in the first story. The subsequent nine stories detail the various downfalls and wild tales of the nine or so (I lost count) generations after him. Like Garcia Marquez's "One Hundred Years of Solitude," this story has a mythic and surreal feel to it. Unlike Garcia Marquez, however, Mahfouz's story is stripped bare of sensuality, yet it is anything but dry. I usually like books with more sumptuously fleshed-out characters, but here, the stark simplicity of the descriptions and Mahfouz's ability to move from one moment in a story to the next with such flawless agility were amazing and compelling. <br /><br />I kept thinking about how to work this book into a study of stories about gangs, because these stories are all about politics and power as various families vie for the coveted position of clan chief. If you read this book, I recommend trying to get through each story in one (or not more than 2) sittings, because, after a while, there are so many characters to keep track of. </span>
  <a data-text-id="2237889800089347189" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


